prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We want to observe in band-7, single continuum mode, with dual polarization. The four basebands (all 1.875 GHz wide) will be filled with continuum spectral windows. Band-7 continuum observations provide good constraint on the star-formation rate (SFR) of our targets. In addition, it provides a clean measurement of the SFR in the QSO host galaxies with minimal contamination from the QSO dust torus. We choose the widest bandwidth for maximum efficiency.

Our proposal is a detection experiment. We expect our sources to be unresolved at an angular resolution of 1 arcsec. According to ALMA observations of sub-millimetre galaxies (SMGs) (e.g., Simpson et al. 2015), these sources are not resolved at angular resolution above 0.8-1". We expect QSOs to be more compact objects than the SMGs.

On the basis of SED fitting to the median flux densities at 250, 350 and 500 microns, the predicted median 870 micron flux density of our QSO targets is 1.0, 1.4 and 1.7 mJy in three redshift bins z=[1.0, 1.5], [1.5, 2.0] and [2.0, 2.5] respectively. The requested sensitivity would give between 5 and 8 sigma detections, depending on the redshift bin. Clearly some QSO targets would not be detected above 5 sigma because they are fainter than the predicted median 870 micron flux. However, as we use the median flux for time estimate, we expect statistically 50 percent of our targets will be detected above 5 sigma.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Directly testing the co-evolution of black hole (BH) growth and star formation is a major goal in astrophysics. An important piece of evidence for co-evolution is the similarity between the cosmic star-formation history (CSFH) and the evolution of the QSO luminosity function. However, due to the brightness of QSOs, CSFH measurements have excluded QSO hosts. We propose for band-7 continuum observations of a complete sample of 150 optically selected SDSS QSOs in the redshift range z=1-2.5. Our main goal is to directly measure the star-formation rate (SFR) distribution function of the QSO hosts across the peak epoch of the CSFH and BH accretion history. We will compare the evolution of the QSO luminosity function and the SFR distribution function in the same systems, providing direct evidence to test co-evolution for the first time. The second goal is to measure the correlation between BH properties (mass and accretion rate) and SFR, and their evolution, and in particular search for evidence of the quenching of star formation by the QSO. Importantly, our optical QSOs have much higher luminosities (where AGN feedback effect could be most obvious) than X-ray AGN in cycle 1 and 2.
